<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-494-895  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 494 895.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Oct 12 1990 n1531* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Commercial partners slam Germany's coolness to the Suprenumsupercomputer.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Suprenum GmbH (finance).andO;Topic:     GermanyResearch and DevelopmentSupercomputersComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>COMMERCIAL PARTNERS SLAM GERMANY'SCOOLNESS TO THEandM;SUPRENUM SUPERCOMPUTERandM;Germany's ambitious Suprenum supercomputer project continues to be beset withdifficulties.andP;  Since the Bundesministerium fr Forschung und Technologie(state ministry for research and development) ended support at the end oflast year, it is said that it will cost firms with shares in Suprenum GmbHthe equivalent of around $20m to bring the project to a successfulconclusion, Computerwoche reports.andP;  Karl Friedrich Triebold, chairman ofshareholder Krupp-Atlas GmbH, explains that half of the sum could come fromindustry, if only the Bundesministerium would stop being so negative towardsthe continuation of the project.andP;  According to Triebold, they can't sell thecomputers in Germany without the support of the research ministry, becausethe first customers would be recruited from the Kreis derGrossforschungs-Einrichtungen and the universities.andP;  If the governmentdoesn't reach a positive decision within six weeks, Triebold continues,Suprenum will have to look for a foreign partnership - possibly even from theUS or Japan, although as long as any state involvement continues, no deal canbe struck with a foreign firm, and it is written into the shareholders'contracts that the fruits of their development must be withheld fromcompetitors for three years.andO;</TEXT></DOC>